# Workflow

Full rules in `DEVELOPMENT.md`. What follows is the short form plus
operational details that bite on Windows.

## TDD slice loop (mandatory)

1. Design note (1-2 paragraphs in the chat) before any code.
2. Write tests in all four categories that apply: **core behaviour**,
   **edge cases**, **breaking tests** (NaN/Infinity/zero/negative/
   out-of-domain for every numeric & enum parameter), **invariants**
   (property-style grids).
3. Run tests — **confirm red for the right reason** before implementing.
4. Implement the minimum to go green.
5. Run `npm test` (all files) and `npm run typecheck`. Both must be clean.
6. Walk the DoD checklist from `DEVELOPMENT.md` §3 explicitly.
7. Commit (one slice = one commit).

Do not merge steps 2 and 4. Do not commit without the DoD walk.

## Commit message format

- Title: `<area>: <imperative present-tense summary>`, lowercase area
  matching a directory under `src/` (e.g. `shared`, `sizing`, `main`),
  or `docs` / `chore` / `tests` for non-source changes.
- Body: what changed and why, not how. Reference the slice in the
  milestone roadmap if applicable.

## PowerShell + git gotchas (this repo runs on Windows)

- **No heredoc in `git commit -m`.** PowerShell parses `<<` as
  redirection and fails. Write the message to a file (e.g.
  `.git/COMMIT_EDITMSG_slice.txt`) with the Write tool, then
  `git commit -F <path>`, then delete the file **sequentially** — not
  in a parallel tool batch, or git will race the delete.
- `ls -la` and `head` are not recognised. Use
  `Get-ChildItem -Force | Select-Object ...` and `Select-Object -First N`
  / `Select-Object -Last N` instead.
- Use `Select-String -Pattern ...` (PowerShell native) or `rg` over
  piping to `grep`.

## Dependencies

- No new runtime dependencies without discussing scope first. M0, M1,
  and M2 slices 1–4a all shipped with zero non-stdlib runtime deps.
  Approved upcoming adds (each in its own slice/commit, alongside an
  `ARCHITECTURE.md` "Technology stack" table update):
  - M2 slice 4b: `dukascopy-node` (Dukascopy URL layout + holiday
    calendar; we still own bi5 parsing in `shared/dukascopy/bi5.ts`).
  - M2 slice 6: `duckdb` (Parquet read + 1 s → arbitrary TF aggregation).
  - Pure-JS `lzma` deliberately *not* taken — `dukascopy-node` handles
    LZMA internally, and a second native module surface isn't worth it
    on the offline-only ingest path.
- Dev deps (Vitest, TypeScript, `@types/node`) stay pinned to major
  versions compatible with Node 22. Do **not** bump `@types/node` past
  `^22` while the runtime stays on Node 22.

## I/O adapter seam pattern (M2 onward)

When introducing an I/O-bound module (filesystem, DuckDB, Dukascopy,
…), put the seam at the **library boundary**, not below it:

- Define a small `interface XClient { … }` in the adapter file.
- Export a `createXClient(opts)` factory that returns the real
  implementation wrapping the third-party library.
- Consumers of `XClient` (the orchestrator) unit-test themselves by
  injecting a hand-written fake `XClient` with canned responses. They
  do **not** mock HTTP / fs underneath the library.
- The adapter's own unit tests (`<adapter>.test.ts`) fake the
  adapter's direct dependencies (`fetch`, `lzma.decompress`, …) — one
  layer below `XClient`, one layer above the third-party library. See
  `src/main/data/dukascopyClient.test.ts`.
- Real-library exercise lives in a separate `<adapter>.network.test.ts`
  file gated by an env var (`HINDSIGHT_RUN_NETWORK=1`) and skipped by
  default in `npm test`.

Rationale: faking below the library means re-implementing its URL
layout / file format / quirks, which defeats the point of using it.

## Integration tests

An integration test exercises **two or more real production modules
together**, with no inter-module mocks. File pattern:
`<orchestrator>.integration.test.ts`, co-located with the higher-level
module of the pair. Picked up by the default `src/**/*.test.ts` glob,
so they run in `npm test` like unit tests.

Two flavours, both following the same four-block layout as unit tests:

- **Pure-composition** — both modules are pure (no I/O). Pin
  cross-module contracts (data shapes, error ownership, boundary
  semantics). Example: `src/shared/bars/aggregate.integration.test.ts`
  composes `decodeBi5Records` and `ticksToSecondBars`, asserting
  bi5-layer parse errors stay `InvalidBi5Error` (never reframed),
  bi5's lax ordering is rejected by aggregate, inverted-spread
  artefacts round-trip untouched.
- **I/O-bound** — at least one module touches the filesystem, SQLite,
  DuckDB, Parquet, or a child process. Use
  `fs.mkdtempSync(path.join(os.tmpdir(), "hindsight-"))` per test,
  clean in `afterEach`, never share a tmpdir, never mock `fs` /
  `sqlite` / `duckdb`.

Network tests (`<adapter>.network.test.ts`) are a separate, opt-in
category — see the seam pattern above.
